# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: courts-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:courts-of-scotland/accountant-in-bankruptcy] It reports to the Scottish Government's Minister for Business, Fair Work and Skills, who is Jamie Hepburn MSP.
[src:courts-of-scotland/accountant-in-bankruptcy] The agency is based in Pennyburn Road, Kilwinning, Ayrshire.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] An **Act of Adjournal** is secondary legislation made by the High Court of Justiciary, the supreme criminal court of Scotland, to regulate the proceedings of Scottish courts hearing criminal matters.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] Now primarily derived from the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, the original power to create Acts of Adjournal is derived from an Act of the Parliament of Scotland in 1672.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] Before promulgation, Acts of Adjournal are reviewed and may be commented upon by the Criminal Courts Rules Council.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] Following Scottish devolution and the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, Acts of Adjournal are made as Scottish Statutory Instruments.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] Before devolution, acts were made as United Kingdom statutory instruments.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] 40) (originally *Act concerning the regulation of the judicatories*) created the High Court of Justiciary by attaching five Lords of Session to the Lord Justice General and Lord Justice Clerk.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] The act provided that "the judges of that court [...] regulate the inferior officers thereof, and order every other thing concerning the said court," a provision which remains in force and which created the distinction between Acts of Adjournal and Acts of Sederunt.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] In the 19th century, a reforming of the High Court of Justiciary made all Lords of Session *ex officio* Lords Commissioners of Justiciary.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-adjournal] That reformation, while now repealed, is replicated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, which further provides that the Lord President of the Court of Session is to hold the office of Lord Justice General.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] An **Act of Sederunt** (/səˈdɛrənt/ *sə-DERR-ənt*; meaning a meeting or sitting of a court) is secondary legislation made by the Court of Session, the supreme civil court of Scotland, to regulate the proceedings of Scottish courts and tribunals hearing civil matters.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Originally made under an Act of the Parliament of Scotland of 1532, the modern power to make Acts of Sederunt is largely derived from the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Since 2013, draft Acts have also been prepared by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and submitted to the Court of Session for approval.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Following Scottish devolution and the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, Acts of Sederunt are made as Scottish statutory instruments.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Previously, Acts were made as United Kingdom statutory instruments, and before that were a separate class of legislation.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session—more accurately the College of Justice—was established by the Parliament of Scotland under James V in 1532.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The act of Parliament establishing the Court, later named the College of Justice Act 1532 (c.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Although established in 1532, it was not until the passing of the **College of Justice Act 1540** (March c.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] 10 (S)), also known as the Act of Sederunt 1540 (originally titled *Ratification of the institution of the college of justice*) that the Court of Session gained the power to make law through Acts of Sederunt.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Courts Act 1672 (originally *Act concerning the regulation of the judicatories*) created the High Court of Justiciary, the supreme criminal court of Scotland, by attaching five of the Lords of Session to the Lord Justice General and Lord Justice Clerk.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Courts Act also provided that "the judges of that court ... regulate the inferior officers thereof, and order every other thing concerning the said court", and so created the distinction between Acts of Sederunt and Acts of Adjournal which continues to exist to this day.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Following a 19th-century reforming of the High Court of Justiciary, all Lords of Session were *ex officio* Lords Commissioners of Justiciary, instead of the original five ordained by the Courts Act.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Although that reformation was repealed, its effect was replicated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, which provided that the Lord President of the Court of Session was also to hold the office of Lord Justice General.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The powers of the Court of Session to make Acts of Sederunt were partially consolidated by the Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933, which also made significant changes to the structure and operations of the Court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] One of these significant changes was the establishing of a Rules Council, composed of the Lord President as well as Court of Session judges and practising lawyers, to propose Acts of Sederunt to the Court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Act also created a Sheriff Court Rules Council, to carry out the same functions but in relation to the sheriff courts.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Sheriff Courts (Scotland) Act 1971 enabled the Court of Session to regulate the sheriff courts and Sheriff Appeal Court when they heard civil matters.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Act also dissolved the Sheriff Court Rules Council created by the Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933, and created a new Sheriff Court Rules Council to continually review sheriff court procedure and submit to the Court of Session draft Acts of Sederunt for regulating sheriff courts.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session Act 1988 was another consolidating act, now with sections relating to Acts of Sederunt largely repealed or modified by the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014, that also altered the structure of the Court of Session.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The remaining powers to make Acts of Sederunt relate to summary trials—although the actual power is now derived from the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014—and the considering of applications to appeal to the Inner House by a single judge.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session Rules Council and Sheriff Court Rules Council were dissolved by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and Criminal Legal Assistance Act 2013, which established the Scottish Civil Justice Council as their replacement.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] (Scotland) Act 2016 to include draft inquiry procedure rules.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session's power to create Acts of Sederunt was extended by the Inquiries into Fatal Accidents and Sudden Deaths etc.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] (Scotland) Act 2016 to include the power to regulate the practice and procedure of public inquiries and fatal accident inquiries.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] As with other secondary legislation, an Act of Sederunt can only make law within the scope set out by an enabling act—an item of primary legislation from which power to make secondary legislation is derived.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] A non-exhaustive summary of these powers is provided below.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] In exercising these powers, the Court of Session can amend or repeal any enactment, including primary legislation, if it relates to matters an Act of Sederunt may cover.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Note, however, that the power to regulate admission into the Faculty of Advocates is effectively delegated from the Court of Session to the Faculty, as the Court legislated to require that those seeking admission meet criteria set out by the Faculty.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Rules for the functioning of the Court of Session are developed by the Scottish Civil Justice Council, which was established by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and Criminal Legal Assistance Act 2013.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The Council prepares draft rules of procedure for the civil courts and advises the Lord President on the development of the civil justice system in Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] The SCJC will consider changes to practice and procedure in response to policy initiatives, by specific request, or of its own accord.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Membership of the council is provided for in the 2013 Act.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Rules for the functioning of civil procedure in the sheriff courts are also prepared by the Scottish Civil Justice Council.
[src:courts-of-scotland/act-of-sederunt] Acts of Sederunt, like other legislation in the United Kingdom, are introduced by enacting formulae.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:courts-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Adjudication can also refer to the processes at dance competitions, in television game shows and at other competitive forums, by which competitors are evaluated and ranked and a winner is found.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Adjudication may be defined as "the legal process of resolving a dispute.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The formal giving or pronouncing of a judgment or decree in a court proceeding; also the judgment or decision given.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The entry of a decree by a court in respect to the parties in a case.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] It implies a hearing by a court, after notice, of legal evidence on the factual issue(s) involved; it may be equivalent to a determination.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] It indicates that the claims of all the parties there to have been considered and set at rest." In some cases, an application for adjudication is an alternative legal process instead of applying for a court hearing.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Each state and territory has enacted security of payment legislation which provide for adjudication of progress construction claims, starting with New South Wales in 1999.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] There is very little harmony between the legislation in each jurisdiction regarding the scope of contract covered and the adjudication procedure.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] However, in all jurisdictions, adjudications are interim pending final resolution of the dispute under the relevant terms of the contract.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The *Building and Construction Industry Security of Payment Act 1999* came into effect in New South Wales on 26 March 2000 and applies to all construction contracts commenced on or after that date.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] It is not possible to contract out of the legislation.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Amendments to the Act made in 2013 are not retrospective, however, earlier amendments are.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The Act does not apply to mining work, however, construction work ancillary to the operation of a mine is covered.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The Act also does not apply to work undertaken for a resident owner within the meaning of the *Home Building Act 1989*.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] In NSW, the 2016 case of *Probuild Constructions (Aust) Pty Ltd v Shade Systems Pty Ltd* has allowed an adjudicator's determination for a non-jurisdictional error to be overturned through judicial review.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The case went against *Brodyn Pty Ltd v Davenport* (2004), which had held that judicial intervention was limited to cases of a breach of essential and basic requirements.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The Building and Construction Industry Payments Act 2004 (BCIPA) came into effect in Queensland in October, 2004.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Through a statutory-based adjudication process a claimant can seek to resolve payment on account disputes.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The act covers construction, and related supply of goods and services, contracts, whether written or verbal.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] BCIPA is regulated by the Building and Construction Industry Payments Agency, a branch of the Queensland Building Services.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Adjudication is a relatively new process introduced by the government of Victoria, Australia, to allow for the rapid determination of progress claims under building contracts or sub-contracts and contracts for the supply of goods or services in the building industry.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] This process was designed to ensure cash flow to businesses in the building industry, without parties getting tied up in lengthy and expensive litigation or arbitration.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] It is regulated by the Building and Construction Industry Security of Payment Act 2002.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Builders, sub-contractors and suppliers need to carefully choose a nominating authority to which they make an adjudication application.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Adjudication is used in relation to construction disputes in Nigeria, although there is no statutory framework for adjudication under Nigerian law.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Lawyers at Stren & Blan Partners note that "recent trends indicate a shift towards adjudication, exemplified by notable settlements in major construction disputes".
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The relevant legislation in regard to construction in the United Kingdom is the Housing Grants, Construction and Regeneration Act 1996 (1996 Chapter 53), later amended by Part 8 of the Local Democracy, Economic Development and Construction Act 2009.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Any party to a construction contract has the right to refer a dispute arising under the contract to a third party for adjudication, whose decision shall be binding unless the courts or an arbitrator have already made a determination on the referred issue.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The Act does not define "adjudication" or an "adjudicator", but an adjudicator's obligation is to act "impartially" (section 108(2)(e)).
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The parties can agree between themselves who will undertake the adjudication, but where they cannot agree, either party may ask an **Adjudicator Nominating Body** (ANB) to appoint one.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] In Scotland, the Scheme for Construction Contracts (Scotland) Regulations 1998 apply.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] For there to be a dispute capable of being addressed by adjudication, "it must be clear that a point has emerged from the process of discussion or negotiation that has ended and that there is something which needs to be decided".
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] In the case of *Aspect Contracts (Asbestos) Limited (Respondent) v Higgins Construction Plc (Appellant)*, heard in 2015, the Supreme Court of England and Wales argued that the wording would have been clearer if had said "unless and until" instead of merely "until".
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The phrase "true value adjudication" is sometimes used in relation to the role of an adjudicator, meaning that the adjudicator is asked to determine the true value of a completed construction where this may be different from the value claimed by the contractor and/or paid by the client.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] In other circumstances, an adjudicator's ruling is binding and a point which has been resolved cannot be raised again, but where the adjudicator went outside the scope of the adjudication referred to them, their comments were not a binding part of the ruling.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] In the same case, reference is made to a 2006 Court of Appeal ruling, *Carillion Construction v Devonport Royal Dockyard*, in which Lord Justice Chadwick reminded litigants that in the UK context, "the majority of adjudicators are not chosen for their expertise as lawyers.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Their skills are as likely (if not more likely) to lie in other disciplines.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The task of the adjudicator is not to act as arbitrator or judge.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The time constraints within which he is expected to operate are proof of that.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] "Claims adjudication" is a phrase used in the insurance industry to refer to the process of paying claims submitted or denying them after comparing claims to the benefit or coverage requirements.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The adjudication process consists of receiving a claim from an insured person and then utilizing software to process claims and make a decision or doing so manually.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] If it is done automatically using software or a web-based subscription, the claim process is called auto-adjudication.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Automating claims often improve efficiency and reduce expenses required for manual claims adjudication.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Many claims are submitted on paper and are processed manually by insurance workers.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] After the claims adjudication process is complete, the insurance company often sends a letter to the person filing the claim describing the outcome.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The letter, which is sometimes referred to as remittance advice, includes a statement as to whether the claim was denied or approved.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] If the company denied the claim, it has to provide an explanation for the reason why under regional laws.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The company also often sends an explanation of benefits that includes detailed information about how each service included in the claim was settled.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Insurance companies will then send out payments to the providers if the claims are approved or to the provider's billing service.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] The process of claims adjudication, in this context, is also called "medical billing advocacy".
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] It may be determined that the person is not suitable for a public trust position, but is suitable for a non-sensitive position.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] However, a person may be deemed unsuitable for any position.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Referring to a minor, the term **adjudicated** can refer to children who are under a court's jurisdiction, usually as a result of having engaged in delinquent behavior and not having a legal guardian that could be entrusted with being responsible for him or her.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] A child dependency or neglect adjudication can also result in a determination that a child is in need of services.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Different US states have different processes for declaring a child as adjudicated.
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] Arizona state law defines a dually adjudicated child as "a child who is found to be dependent or temporarily subject to court jurisdiction pending an adjudication of a dependency petition and who is alleged or found to have committed a delinquent or incorrigible act".
[src:courts-of-scotland/adjudication] According to Illinois state law, "adjudicated" means that the Juvenile Court has entered an order declaring that a child "is neglected, abused, dependent, a minor requiring authoritative intervention, a delinquent minor or an addicted minor".
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] The **Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933** (23 & 24 Geo.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] 41) is an act of the Parliament at Westminster legislating for Scotland which introduced changes in Scottish legal procedure "following the recommendations of a Royal Commission which reported in 1927".
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] The act was introduced following the Royal Commission on the Court of Session and the Office of Sheriff Principal.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] The act abolished the ancient practice of a trial (or examination) of qualifications of a nominee for appointment as a judge of the Court of Session (s.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] 3) and an additional division of the Inner House was created (s.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] It provided new arrangements for the sittings of judges (granting them a power to extend a session if required) and for the work of the vacation judge (s.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] Provisions were made for the appointment of officers of the High Court of Justiciary and the Court of Session and their superannuation arrangements.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] The act ended the right of parties to choose the judge (Lord Ordinary) or Division for the hearing of their causes or appeals (s.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] It simplified the form of proceedings (ss.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] 6-9) and created a procedure to allow summary trial (by a judge without a jury) (s.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] A procedure for a simple majority verdict by a jury was introduced (majority verdicts had long been available to criminal juries in Scotland).
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] Provision for made for situations where a juror died or became unfit to continue serving (s.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] A Rules Council for the Court of Session and another for the Sheriff Courts were established fashioned on the Rule Committee of the Supreme Court in England.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] They were given a power to draft rules regarding any matters about which Acts of Sederunt may be made.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] These were then to be submitted to the Court which might enact them (with or without amendment) in an Act of Sederunt.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] Both Scottish Rules Councils included representatives of the judiciary and the two branches of the legal profession (advocates and solicitors); and the Lord President of the Court of Session was made an *ex officio* member of both Councils.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] The statutory power to make acts of Sederunt granted in sections 16 and 17 of the act was consolidated and replaced by sections 5 and 6 of the *Court of Session Act* 1988 (UK).
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] A power to reorganise the then fifteen territorial sheriffs and the sheriff of Chancery was created.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] The Secretary of State for Scotland was permitted to form new sheriffdoms by uniting two or more counties or parts of counties should a vacancy occur in the office of sheriff; but such orders were not to take effect until both Houses of Parliament have resolved to approved them.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] After commencement of the act, new Rules of Court for the Court of Session were embodied by Act of Sederunt in 1934.
[src:courts-of-scotland/administration-of-justice-scotland-act-1933] "The purpose of these Rules is not to provide a comprehensive summary of Court of Session procedure, but to reform and extend the existing procedure so far as necessary to adapt it to the new conditions created by the act ....
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The **courts of Scotland** (Scottish Gaelic: *Cùirtean na h-Alba*) are responsible for administration of justice in Scotland, under statutory, common law and equitable provisions within Scots law.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The courts are presided over by the judiciary of Scotland, who are the various judicial office holders responsible for issuing judgments, ensuring fair trials, and deciding on sentencing.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The judiciary of Scotland, except the Lord Lyon King of Arms, are united under the leadership and authority of the Lord President and Lord Justice General, who is the president of the Court of Session and High Court of Justiciary.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Court of Session has the authority, under the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014, to regulate civil procedure through passing subordinate legislation knows as Acts of Sederunt, and the High Court of Justiciary has the authority to regulate criminal procedure through passing Acts of Adjournal.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Both Acts of Sederunt and Acts of Adjournal have the capacity to amend primary legislation where it deals with civil or criminal procedure respectively.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The majority of criminal and civil justice in Scotland is handled by the local sheriff courts, which are arranged into six sheriffdoms led by a sheriff principal.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The sheriff courts have exclusive jurisdiction over all civil cases with a monetary value up to £100,000, and are able to try criminal cases both on complaint for summary offences, and with a jury for indictable offences.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Treason, murder, and rape are in the exclusive jurisdiction of the High Court of Justiciary, and whilst the High Court and sheriff courts have concurrent jurisdiction over armed robbery, drug trafficking, and sexual offences involving children virtually all these cases are heard by the High Court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Administration for the courts is provided by the Scottish Courts and Tribunals Service, a non-ministerial department of the Scottish Government.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Scottish Courts and Tribunal Service is operationally independent of the Scottish Ministers, and is governed by a corporate board chaired by the Lord President, and with a majority of judicial members.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] There are various specialist courts and tribunals with specialist jurisdictions, which are subject to the ultimate jurisdiction of either the Court of Session or High Court of Justiciary.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Children under the age of 16 who face allegations of criminal conduct are dealt with through the Children's Hearings, which are quasi-judicial in nature.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Disputes involving agricultural tenancies and crofting are dealt with by the Scottish Land Court, and disputes about private rights in titles for land ownership and land valuation are dealt with by the Lands Tribunal for Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Heraldry is regulated in Scotland both by the civil and criminal law, with prosecutions taken before the Court of the Lord Lyon.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Defunct and historical courts include the Admiralty Court, Court of Exchequer, district courts, and the High Court of Constabulary.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The United Kingdom does not have a single judicial system – England and Wales have one system, Scotland another, and Northern Ireland a third.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The military courts of the United Kingdom have jurisdiction over all members of the armed forces of the United Kingdom and civilians subject to service discipline in relation to offences against military law.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Supreme Court of the United Kingdom operates across all three separate jurisdictions, hearing some civil – but not criminal – appeals in Scottish cases, and determining certain devolution and human rights issues.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Supreme Court of the United Kingdom was created on 1 October 2009 by the Constitutional Reform Act 2005.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Supreme Court hears civil appeals from the Court of Session, and it hears appeals from all the civil and criminal courts of England and Wales and of Northern Ireland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Supreme Court has no authority to hear appeals on criminal matters from the High Court of Justiciary.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Until the creation of the Supreme Court, ultimate appeal lay to the House of Lords, a chamber of the Parliament of the United Kingdom (though in modern practice only the Law Lords sitting in the Appellate Committee, rather than the whole House, heard appeals).
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Supreme Court took over the judicial functions of the House of Lords, and also assumed the jurisdiction over devolution and human rights issues vested in the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Cases involving "devolution issues" arising under the Scotland Act 1998, as amended by the Scotland Act 2016, which includes disputes regarding the validity of Acts of the Scottish Parliament or executive functions of the Scottish Government, are heard by the Supreme Court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Court system in its modern form is based on the reforms introduced by Lord Gill as Lord President, and implemented or further modified under the Lord Presidency of Lord Carloway.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The foundational legislation for the sheriff courts and many other changes is the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Court of Session is the supreme civil court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] It is both a court of first instance and a court of appeal, and sits exclusively in Parliament House in Edinburgh.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The court of first instance is known as the Outer House, the court of appeal the Inner House.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Sheriff Appeal Court is a national court with a jurisdiction over civil appeals from the sheriff courts, and replaces appeals previously made to the sheriffs principal.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Sheriff Appeal Court is a national court with a jurisdiction over appeals in summary criminal proceedings, and bail decisions in solemn procedure, from the sheriff courts and justice of the peace courts.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Sheriff Appeal Court had its jurisdiction extended on 1 January 2016, when the provisions of the Court Reform (Scotland) Act 2014 to extend civil appeals to the Sheriff Appeal Court were brought into force by the Scottish Ministers.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Sheriff Personal Injury Court is a specialist all-Scotland court with exclusive competence to hear cases, with and without a jury, that relate to personal injury.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Personal Injury Court has concurrent jurisdiction with local sheriff courts, over claims relating to personal injury where the case is for a work-related accident claim in excess of £1,000, or where the total amount claimed is in excess of £5,000.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The choice of local sheriff court or the Personal Injury Court is left to the pursuer.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] However, where a sheriff believes the case is so complex as to require the specialist expertise of the personal injury sheriffs they can remit the case to the Sheriff Personal Injury Court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] In Scotland, all monetary claims for amounts not in excess of £100,000 are in the exclusive jurisdiction of the sheriff courts, with the Court of Session having concurrent jurisdiction for amounts of more than £100,000.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Personal Injury Court was established by the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014 and the All-Scotland Sheriff Court (Sheriff Personal Injury Court) Order 2015.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The sheriff courts are the other civil courts; they sit locally.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Any final decision of a sheriff may be appealed against.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] There is a right of appeal in civil cases to the Sheriff Appeal Court, and, with permission, to the Inner House of the Court of Session.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The High Court of Justiciary is the supreme criminal court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The High Court is both a court of first instance and also a court of appeal.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] As a court of first instance, the High Court sits mainly in the Justiciary Building in the Lawnmarket in Edinburgh and in the Justiciary Buildings in the Saltmarket in Glasgow, but also sits from time to time in various other places in Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] As a court of appeal, it sits only in Edinburgh.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Appeals may be made to the High Court of Justiciary sitting as the Court of Criminal Appeal from the lower courts in criminal cases.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] An appeal may also be made to the High Court if the High Court itself heard the case at first instance.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Two judges sit to hear an appeal against sentence, and three judges sit to hear an appeal against conviction.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] There is no further appeal from the High Court's decision on appeal, in contrast to the Court of Session, from which it is possible to appeal to the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom, the highest court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Appeals under the Human Rights Act 1998 and devolution appeals under the Scotland Act 1998 are heard by the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom (previously these were head by the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council).
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Sheriff Appeal Court is a national court with jurisdiction over appeals from summary criminal proceedings in the sheriff courts and justice of the peace courts, and from bail decision in solemn procedure at the sheriff court.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Sheriff Appeal Court was established on 22 September 2015 to deal with appeals against conviction and sentence in summary proceedings before the deal with criminal appeals.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The bench generally comprises three appeal sheriffs when considering appeals against conviction, and two appeal sheriffs when considering appeals against sentence.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] A single appeal sheriff hears appeals against bail decisions made by a sheriff or justices of the peace.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The court is based at the courthouse at Lawnmarket, Edinburgh, and initially sat on two consecutive days each fortnight.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Substantive criminal appeals are now heard on Tuesdays and appeals against sentence on Wednesdays.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The sheriff courts are the main criminal courts; they sit locally in sheriff courts throughout Scotland organised in the six sheriffdoms.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The procedure followed may either be solemn procedure, where the Sheriff sits with a jury of fifteen; or summary procedure, where the sheriff sits alone in a bench trial.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] From 10 December 2007, the maximum penalty that may be imposed in summary cases is 12 months imprisonment or a £10,000 fine, and in solemn cases 5 years imprisonment or an unlimited fine.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] A higher sentence in solemn cases may be imposed upon remittance of the case to the High Court of Justiciary.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Justice of the peace courts are criminal courts which sit locally under summary procedure, where the justice sits alone or in some areas as a bench of three.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Justices are lay magistrates who as advised by a legally qualified clerk, known as the legal adviser.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The court handles a variety of minor common law crimes such as breach of the peace, theft and assault, as well as statutory offences such as vandalism, road traffic offences and other public order offences.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The maximum penalty which can be imposed at this level is 60 days' imprisonment or a fine up to £2,500.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Scotland has several courts with specialist jurisdictions.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The specialist system of children's hearings handles the majority of cases involving allegations of criminal conduct involving persons under 16 in Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] These tribunals have wide-ranging powers to issue supervision orders for the person referred to them by the Scottish Children's Reporter Administration.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Serious crimes, at the direction of a procurator fiscal, are still dealt with in the usual criminal courts.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Court of the Lord Lyon, the standing court of heraldry and genealogy, is responsible for civil and criminal enforcement of armorial bearings and the right to use certain titles.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] It is headed by the Lord Lyon, who is King of Arms and senior herald for Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Lands Valuation Appeal Court is a Scottish civil court, composed of three Court of Session judges, and established under section 7 of the Valuation of Lands (Scotland) Amendment Act 1879.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] It hears cases where the decision of a local Valuation Appeal Committee is disputed.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The senators who make up the Lands Valuation Appeal Court were specified in 2013 by the Act of Sederunt (Lands Valuation Appeal Court) 2013, which has both Lord Carloway (Lord President) and Lady Dorrian (Lord Justice Clerk) as members with a further four senators specified.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Scottish Land Court has jurisdiction over disputes involving agricultural tenancies and crofting rights.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Under the terms of the Church of Scotland Act 1921 the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland has sole jurisdiction over its own spiritual affairs, including matters of discipline.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] There are several specialist tribunals in Scotland which often have exclusive jurisdiction over cases relevant to their remit.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] They are subject to the oversight and ultimate authority of the Court of Session, which can review decisions through either a final appeal or through judicial review.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] There are several tribunals that have jurisdiction either over the whole United Kingdom, or over Great Britain.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Where these tribunals make an adjudication in Scotland they are subject to the oversight and ultimate authority of the Court of Session, which can review decisions either through a final appeal or through judicial review.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] When an Employment Tribunal makes a determination in Scotland it is subject to practice directions from the President of Employment Tribunals (Scotland), and operates under Scots law.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] These tribunals are administered by His Majesty's Courts and Tribunals Service.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] In many cases there is a statutory right of appeal from a tribunal either to an upper tribunal or senior tribunal, or to the Court of Session: for example Employment Tribunal cases are appealed to the Employment Appeal Tribunal, which in turn allows appeals to the Court of Session.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] In the absence of a specific appeals court, the only remedy from a decision of a Tribunal is an appeal to, or judicial review by, the Court of Session, which will often be more limited in scope than an appeal.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Bill Chamber was formerly a court of Scotland, often considered as part of the Court of Session but in fact separate from it.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] It dealt with petitions for suspension (appeal), interdict, sequestrations etc., and was the approximate equivalent to sittings *in camera* (in chambers) in American or English law.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Bill Chamber was "under the same roof" as the Court of Session, but was a separate court or jurisdiction.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Some of its processes are now carried out by the Accountant in Bankruptcy.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The judges of the Court were the Barons of Exchequer who acted in both a judicial capacity, dealing with revenue cases, debts to the crown, seizure of smuggled goods and prosecutions for illicit brewing and distilling, and in an administrative capacity, mainly auditing accounts.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The president of the Exchequer Court was known as the Chief Baron of Exchequer, and the initial president was the Lord High Treasurer.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The 1707 Act limited the numbers of Barons to 5.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] A separate Exchequer Court was abolished by the Exchequer Court (Scotland) Act 1856, and all of its powers were transferred to the Court of Session.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] With its abolishment no further Barons of Exchequer were appointed.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] District courts are no longer in existence.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] They were introduced in 1975 and sat in each local council area under summary procedure only.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Scottish Government merged the management of the sheriff and justice of the peace courts (formerly known as district courts), retaining lay justices.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] (Reform) (Scotland) Act 2007 enabled the Scottish Ministers to replace district courts by "justice of the peace courts".
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The process is concluded and all district courts are now abolished and replaced with the new justice of the peace courts throughout Scotland, which have strengthened powers to allow more cases to be dealt with at this level.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The High Court of Constabulary was a court in Scotland presided over by the Lord High Constable of Scotland and deputes appointed by the Lord High Constable.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Established in the late 13th century the court was empowered to judge all cases of rioting, disorder, bloodshed, and murder if such crimes occurred within four miles of the King of Scots, the King's Council, or the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] Following James VI's move to England, the jurisdiction of the Lord High Constable was defined in terms of the "resident place" appointed for the Privy Council.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] In 1815, the Jury Trials (Scotland) Act 1815 created the Jury Court to allow certain civil cases to be tried by jury.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] The Jury Court was subordinate to the Court of Session, and appeals were heard by the Inner House of the Court of Session.
[src:courts-of-scotland/courts-of-scotland] In 1830 the Jury Court, along with the Admiralty and Commissary Courts, was absorbed into the Court of Session following the enactment of the Court of Session Act 1830.
